@node Overview
@chapter Overview

@samp{abbrev-extras.el} extends Emacs' built-in abbreviation facility (@samp{abbrev.el}). The standard @samp{add-mode-abbrev} command requires you to be in the target major mode and to have the expansion text in the buffer. This can be inconvenient when you want to define abbreviations for modes you are not currently using or when the expansion is not present in any buffer.

This package provides an interactive command that lets you select any major mode from a completing-read prompt and type both the abbreviation and its expansion as strings (@ref{Adding abbreviations}). It also handles creating the abbrev table if it does not yet exist, and optionally persists the definitions to disk automatically (@ref{@code{abbrev-extras-write-file-p}}).

@node User options
@chapter User options

@menu
* @code{abbrev-extras-write-file-p}::
@end menu

@node @code{abbrev-extras-write-file-p}
@section @code{abbrev-extras-write-file-p}

@vindex abbrev-extras-write-file-p
The user option @code{abbrev-extras-write-file-p} controls whether abbreviation definitions are automatically saved to @code{abbrev-file-name} after adding a new mode-specific abbreviation with @code{abbrev-extras-add-mode-abbrev} (@ref{Adding abbreviations}).

The default value is @code{t}, meaning abbreviations are saved immediately. Set this to @code{nil} if you prefer to accumulate changes in memory and save manually with @code{abbrev-extras-write-abbrevs} (@ref{Writing abbreviations}).

The type is a boolean.

